$\mathbf {X}_{i \cdot }^{g} \in \mathbb {R}^{p_{g}}$
\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M10"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">X</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>·</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>g</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>ℝ</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>g</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2015_556_IEq5.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> for <italic>g</italic>=1,…,<italic>G</italic>.</p>
      <p>We propose a three-step method consisting in (i) performing a spatially constrained hierarchical clustering of the covariates <bold>X</bold>, (ii) estimating the number of groups using (a modified version of) the Gap statistic [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR13">13</xref>], and (iii) performing a Group Lasso regression to identify which of the inferred groups are associated with the response <bold>y</bold>.</p>
      <sec id="Sec4">
        <title>Inference of LD blocks from genotypes</title>
        <p>The first step of the proposed approach consists in inferring LD blocks using a spatially constrained hierarchical clustering algorithm. Only the genotype data <bold>X</bold> are used at this step.</p>
        <p>The proposed clustering procedure is based on the one of the most widely used methods for cluster analysis: Ward’s incremental sum of squares algorithm [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR14">14</xref>]. The general goal of sum of squares clustering is to minimize the total within-group dispersion <italic>W</italic>
<sub><italic>G</italic></sub> for a given number of groups <italic>G</italic>. Denoting by <inline-formula id="IEq6"><alternatives><tex-math id="M11">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$S_{gg'}\phantom {\dot {i}\!}$
\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M12"><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>S</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>g</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo>′</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:msup></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2015_556_IEq6.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> the total squared similarity (usually, the similarity induced by the Euclidean distance) between all pairs of items in groups <italic>g</italic> and <italic>g</italic>
<sup>′</sup>, and by <italic>p</italic>
<sub><italic>g</italic></sub> the size of group <italic>g</italic>, <italic>W</italic>
<sub><italic>G</italic></sub> may be written as
<disp-formula id="Equa"><alternatives><tex-math id="M13">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
